From codeplex:

https://monogame.codeplex.com/discussions/447510#post1060694

For reference of anyone interested: it seems the following lines are not yet fully supported, and therefore cause all primitives to be rendered in black for both the current Master and Develop branch:
//these should not be set, or all is dark is iOS
//effect.EnableDefaultLighting();
//effect.AmbientLightColor = new Vector3(1, 1, 1);  
//effect.DiffuseColor = new Vector3(1, 1, 1);
//effect.LightingEnabled = true;

MojoShader thinks that vertex shaders can't handle tex2Dlod in vs_3_0.

Save this effect file to "bloop.fx":

``` javascript
texture MTexture;
sampler MSampler = sampler_state { texture = <Texture>; };

float4 MVertexShader(float4 position : POSITION) : POSITION
{
    return tex2Dlod(MSampler, float4(0, 0, 0, 0));
}

float4 MPixelShader(float4 position : POSITION) : COLOR
{
    return float4(0, 0, 0, 0);
}

technique
{
    pass
    {
        VertexShader = compile vs_3_0 MVertexShader();
        PixelShader = compile ps_3_0 MPixelShader();
    }
}
```

Compile with "[path]2mgfx bloop.fx bleep.mgfx", and it responds with:

```
fail - invalid DCL register type for this shader model
fail - TEXLD using undeclared sampler
invalid DCL register type for this shader model
Failed to compile the input file 'bloop.fx'!
```

I don't know if it's input from MGFX or a bug in MojoShader, but tex2Dlod was put in Shader Model 3 primarily to allow vertex shader access of samplers. So it's indisputably wrong.

So others have brought up this issue before and it could probably use a better API.

`GraphicsDevice.GetRenderTargets()` currently looks like this:

```
public RenderTargetBinding[] GetRenderTargets()
{
   // Return a correctly sized copy our internal array.
   var bindings = new RenderTargetBinding[_currentRenderTargetCount];
   Array.Copy(_currentRenderTargetBindings, bindings, _currentRenderTargetCount);
   return bindings; 
}
```

The reason is if we return the internal copy of the render target bindings that allows someone from the outside to alter the array.  This is also how Microsoft XNA behaves.

So what would be a better design that doesn't generate garbage?

It seems something like this would do:

```
public int RenderTargetCount { get; }
public void GetRenderTargets(ref RenderTargetBinding[] outTargets);
```

Is there something better?
